{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b2dcd91b-e167-4b75-bd00-6a67d94958ff","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's platform cryptographic libraries (`Security.framework` / `CryptoKit`) have **never supported DSA**. In earlier .NET versions, the runtime shipped an OpenSSL-based shim on macOS to fill the gap. In .NET 11, that fallback was removed — `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS (and iOS/tvOS).\n\nWindows and Linux are unaffected because they have native DSA support (CNG and OpenSSL, respectively).\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), switch to a managed crypto library that doesn't depend on platform APIs:\n\n**Use [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography):**\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\nThen replace the built-in DSA verification:\n\n```csharp\n// Before (.NET 10, platform-dependent)\nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\n\nusing var dsa = DSA.Create();\ndsa.ImportParameters(legacyParameters);\nbool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);\n```\n\n```csharp\n// After (BouncyCastle, cross-platform)\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Math;\n\nvar pubParams = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(\n    new BigInteger(1, legacyParameters.Y),\n    new DsaParameters(\n        new BigInteger(1, legacyParameters.P),\n        new BigInteger(1, legacyParameters.Q),\n        new BigInteger(1, legacyParameters.G)));\n\nvar signer = new DsaDigestSigner(new DsaSigner(),\n    new Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Digests.Sha1Digest());\nsigner.Init(forSigning: false, pubParams);\nsigner.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\nThis runs identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS with no platform crypto dependency.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0b1c21dd-c0eb-4142-ac67-5970feaee39d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue related to DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) and the transition from .NET 10 to .NET 11, specifically on macOS. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Let me recall the details:\n\nIn .NET 7+, Apple's security frameworks (Security.framework / CommonCrypto) dropped support for DSA. .NET on macOS previously used OpenSSL via a shim for DSA operations, but over time, Microsoft has been moving toward using the native platform crypto APIs.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe core issue is that DSA isn't supported on macOS anymore—calling `DSA.Create()` throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` because Apple's native cryptographic libraries don't support it and .NET stopped relying on OpenSSL for this on Apple platforms. This change actually happened around the .NET 7-8 timeframe, so I'm wondering if the user is asking about a real breaking change between .NET 10 and 11 or if this is a hypothetical scenario, since .NET 11 doesn't actually exist yet. The core issue is that `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because Apple's native cryptographic frameworks don't support DSA, and .NET removed the OpenSSL fallback. For verifying legacy signatures, the user would need to either switch to RSA or ECDSA for new work, or find a cross-platform workaround that doesn't rely on the native .NET implementation.\n\nBouncyCastle is the practical solution here—it provides a managed DSA implementation that works consistently across all platforms, so the user can verify those legacy signatures without being blocked by macOS's platform limitations.","outputTokens":1497,"requestId":"D81D:44010:60BAFB1:69F9039:69F16261"},"id":"80da013e-5667-491b-a7d9-b1f4d030a2cf","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:44:33.536Z","parentId":"b7770fbf-d41d-471b-a6e8-bd3994a1ad9a"}
